Carson, this is excellent. You've identified the right problems and your instincts are spot-on. Let me add some specifics and one important refinement.

**1. Adding a todo -- agreed, with one detail**

Your approach is correct. The key architectural decision is that the form lives OUTSIDE the swap target:
```html
<form hx-post="/todos" hx-target="#todo-list" hx-swap="beforeend">
  <label for="new-todo">New todo</label>
  <input type="text" id="new-todo" name="title" autocomplete="off">
  <button type="submit">Add todo</button>
</form>
<ul id="todo-list" aria-label="Todo items">
  <!-- items appended here -->
</ul>
```

Because the input is never swapped, focus stays on it naturally. No focus management code needed for this interaction. The OOB swap to clear the input is the right call -- the server returns the new `<li>` plus an OOB swap that resets the input value.

For the aria-live announcement, I'd include the todo title: "Added: Buy milk" rather than just "Todo added." It confirms what was captured, which is useful when you're rapidly adding items.

**2. Completing a todo -- agreed, with a refinement on the refocus**

The `outerHTML` swap destroys the old checkbox and creates a new one. The browser drops focus to `<body>`. We need to refocus the checkbox in the new element.

My recommendation: put `data-autofocus` on the checkbox in the server-returned HTML:
```html
<li class="todo-item">
  <input type="checkbox" id="todo-{{ id }}" 
         data-autofocus
         hx-patch="/todos/{{ id }}/toggle"
         hx-target="closest li"
         hx-swap="outerHTML"
         {% if completed %}checked{% endif %}>
  <label for="todo-{{ id }}">{{ title }}</label>
  ...
</li>
```

Then the `htmx:afterSwap` handler focuses it:
```javascript
document.addEventListener('htmx:afterSwap', (event) => {
  const autofocusEl = event.detail.target.querySelector('[data-autofocus]');
  if (autofocusEl) {
    autofocusEl.focus();
  }
});
```

Wait -- actually, `event.detail.target` for `outerHTML` swaps might be the parent element. We may need `event.detail.elt` instead. We'll need to test this carefully. The point is: the server tells the client where to put focus via `data-autofocus`, and a single event listener handles all cases.

For the announcement: "Completed: Buy milk" or "Uncompleted: Buy milk" -- the verb confirms the action taken.

**3. Deleting a todo -- the hard one, and I have a concrete proposal**

You're right that this is the hardest. The element is gone, focus drops to `<body>`, keyboard user is lost in space. Here's my concrete approach:

Before the HTMX request fires, we record the context:
```javascript
document.addEventListener('htmx:beforeSwap', (event) => {
  const target = event.detail.elt;
  // If this is a delete (element will be removed), record siblings
  if (target.matches('.todo-item') && event.detail.xhr.status === 200 
      && event.detail.serverResponse.trim() === '') {
    const nextSibling = target.nextElementSibling;
    const prevSibling = target.previousElementSibling;
    const fallback = document.getElementById('new-todo');

    // Store the focus target for afterSwap
    event.detail.target._focusAfterDelete = 
      nextSibling || prevSibling || fallback;
  }
});

document.addEventListener('htmx:afterSwap', (event) => {
  // Handle delete focus
  const focusTarget = event.detail.target._focusAfterDelete;
  if (focusTarget) {
    // Focus the first focusable element within the target
    const focusable = focusTarget.querySelector('input, button, a') || focusTarget;
    focusable.focus();
    delete event.detail.target._focusAfterDelete;
    return;
  }

  // Handle other swaps with data-autofocus
  const autofocusEl = event.detail.elt.querySelector?.('[data-autofocus]') 
    || event.detail.target.querySelector?.('[data-autofocus]');
  if (autofocusEl) {
    autofocusEl.focus();
  }
});
```

Actually, let me simplify. Rather than detecting empty responses, we could use a data attribute on the delete button to signal intent:
```html
<button type="button"
        hx-delete="/todos/{{ id }}"
        hx-target="closest .todo-item"
        hx-swap="outerHTML"
        data-focus-fallback="next-sibling"
        aria-label="Delete {{ title }}">
  Delete
</button>
```

The `data-focus-fallback` attribute tells our focus management script what to do. The script records the sibling before the swap happens. Cleaner separation of concerns -- the HTML declares intent, the script executes it.

**4. Inline editing -- agreed, with Escape key handling**

Your flow is right. One addition: the Escape key handler for cancelling should be on the edit form itself, not globally. We don't want Escape doing unexpected things elsewhere:
```html
<form hx-put="/todos/{{ id }}" 
      hx-target="closest li" 
      hx-swap="outerHTML"
      hx-on:keydown="if(event.key === 'Escape') { 
        htmx.ajax('GET', '/todos/{{ id }}', {target: this.closest('li'), swap: 'outerHTML'}) 
      }">
  <label for="edit-{{ id }}" class="visually-hidden">Edit todo</label>
  <input type="text" id="edit-{{ id }}" name="title" value="{{ title }}" data-autofocus>
  <button type="submit">Save</button>
  <button type="button" 
          hx-get="/todos/{{ id }}" 
          hx-target="closest li" 
          hx-swap="outerHTML">Cancel</button>
</form>
```

After save or cancel, the server returns the display view with `data-autofocus` on the edit button, so focus goes back to where the user initiated the edit. That's the principle of "return focus to origin."

**The unified focus management script**

I think we end up with one small TypeScript file (~30 lines) that handles all focus management:
1. `htmx:beforeSwap` -- records sibling context for deletions
2. `htmx:afterSwap` -- focuses `[data-autofocus]` elements, or handles deletion fallback
3. `htmx:afterSwap` -- updates the `#status-announcer` text for screen reader announcements

This is progressive enhancement: without JS, every interaction is a full page reload and the browser handles focus naturally. With HTMX, the partial swaps are smooth. With this TypeScript layer, focus management is polished.

Three layers. Each enhances the one below. Exactly the progressive enhancement model.

**One pattern you didn't mention: loading/disabled state**

When an HTMX request is in flight, the triggering element should be disabled to prevent double-submission. HTMX has `hx-disabled-elt` for this. But we also need to communicate the loading state to screen readers:
```html
<button hx-delete="/todos/{{ id }}" 
        hx-disabled-elt="this"
        aria-busy="false">
  Delete
</button>
```

And a small HTMX extension or event listener that toggles `aria-busy="true"` during the request. Screen readers will announce "busy" which tells the user something is happening.

Does this all hang together from your perspective? I think we have a solid, unified approach here.

